revision.text:
{{italic title}}
'''''Authors of Plant Names''''' ('''Brummitt & Powell''') by [[Richard Kenneth Brummitt]] and [[C. E. Powell]], 1992, is a print [[database]] of accepted standardized abbreviations used for citing the author who [[Author citation (botany)|validly published]] the name of a [[taxon]].<ref name=Jones>{{cite book |last1=Jones |first1=Stanley D. |last2=Wipff |first2=Joseph K. |last3=Montgomery |first3=Paul M. |title=Vascular Plants of Texas: A Comprehensive Checklist Including Synonymy, Bibliography, and Index |date=1997 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=978-0-292-72962-9 |pages=5–6 |url=http://utpress.utexas.edu/index.php/books/jonvas |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=Davis>{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Elisabeth B.|title=Guide to information sources in the botanical sciences|year=1996|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|location=Englewood, Colo.|isbn=1563080753|page=188|edition=2.|author2=Schmidt, Diane}}</ref>  The database is now maintained online at the [[International Plant Names Index]].<ref name=Kew>{{cite web|title=Authors of Plant Names  Where is the Brummitt & Powell "Authors of Plant Names" database?|url=http://www.kew.org/data/authors.html|publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref> The book provides recommended abbreviations for authors' names that help to distinguish authors with the same [[surname]] when giving the full name of a taxon. It deals authors who validly published the name of a [[flowering plant]], [[gymnosperm]], [[fern]], [[bryophyte]], [[algae]], [[fungi]] or [[fossil plants]].<ref name=Jones/><ref name=Kew/> Prior to its publication in 1992, many abbreviations for authors to be cited could be found in ''Taxonomic literature. A selective guide to botanical publications and collections with dates, commentaries and types.'' by F. A. Stafleu & R. F. Cowen, 1976-1988.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biodiversity Research in the Horn of Africa Region: Proceedings of the Third International Symposium on the Flora of Ethiopia and Eritrea|year=1999|publisher=Carlsberg Academy|location=Copenhagen}}</ref>

The [[International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants]] (ICN) governs the naming of these organisms, and suggests that a taxon be fully identified by its name and the author, but does not require that abbreviations be used when citing an author for a taxon. When abbreviations are used, the ICN recommends that Brummitt & Powell’s ''Authors of plant names'' (1992), and the websites, the International Plant Names Index (www.ipni.org) and the [[Index Fungorum]] (www.indexfungorum.org) can be used to find "unambiguous" abbreviations.<ref name="MelbourneCode">{{Citation |year=2012 |editor-last=McNeill |editor-first=J. |editor2-last=Barrie |editor2-first=F. R. |editor3-last=Buck |editor3-first=W. R. |editor4-last=Demoulin |editor4-first=V.  |title=International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code), Article 46 |edition=electronic |publication-place=Bratislava |publisher=International Association for Plant Taxonomy |url=http://www.iapt-taxon.org/nomen/main.php?page=art46 |accessdate=2012-12-20}}</ref> Brummitt & Powell may not be international in scope, and it may be missing abbreviations for authors who validly published taxa during some time spans.<ref name=Jones/> A full name, rather than an abbreviation, may also make it easier to locate the original publication for the taxon name.<ref name=Jones/>

