{{Infobox person |honorific_prefix = Professor |name = David Norman |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = 1949 |birth_place = |death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |death_place = |death_cause = |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> |residence = |nationality = British |other_names = |known_for = Ornithology |education = |alma_mater = |employer = |occupation = [[Chartered Physicist]], academic |years_active = |home_town = |title = |boards = |spouse = |partner = |children = |parents = |relations = |signature = |website = {{URL |davidnorman.org.uk}} }}
Professor '''David Norman''' (born 1949<ref>{{cite web|url=http://copac.ac.uk/wzgw?id=0811263bf24d7aea51132708cda16eed63446d&f=u&rsn=5&rn=1|title=COPAC entry for ''The Fieldfare''|accessdate=2008-11-26}}</ref>) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Chartered Physicist]]<ref name="EN-acting">{{cite web|url=http://www.english-nature.org.uk/news/story.asp?ID=200 |title=English Nature announce acting Chairman |date=2000-09-28 |publisher=English Nature |accessdate=2008-11-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070722103722/http://www.english-nature.org.uk/news/story.asp?ID=200 |archivedate=2007-07-22 |df= }}</ref> and [[ornithology|ornithologist]], he has lived in [[Cheshire]] since 1978.<ref name="RBBP-pan">{{cite web|url=http://www.rbbp.org.uk/rbbp-panel.htm|title=Current Panel Members|publisher=Rare Breeding Birds Panel|accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref>
==Physics==
Professor Norman is a former Director of Synchrotron Radiation, [[Council for the Central Laboratory of the Research Councils]], [[Daresbury Laboratory]].<ref name="EN-acting" /> He was a visiting Professor in Surface Science at the [[University of Liverpool]].<ref name="EN-acting" />
== Ornithology ==
Since 2005<ref name="BB100:6">{{cite journal|last=Holling|first=Mark |author2=The Rare Breeding Birds Panel|date=June 2007|title=Rare breeding birds in the United Kingdom in 2003 and 2004 |url=http://www.rbbp.org.uk/downloads/rbbp-report-2003-04.pdf |journal=British Birds|volume=100|issue=6|pages=321–367|issn=0007-0335}}</ref> he has been an independent member of the United Kingdom's [[Rare Breeding Birds Panel]]<ref name="RSPB-council">{{cite web|url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/about/run/council.asp |title=RSPB Council |publisher=RSPB |accessdate=2008-11-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303044502/http://www.rspb.org.uk/about/run/council.asp |archivedate=2008-03-03 |df= }}</ref> and he is a member of the [[RSPB]] Council,<ref name="RSPB-council" /> and Chairman of the Merseyside Ringing Group. He is an honorary research associate of the [[Carnegie Museum of Natural History]],<ref name="RSPB-council" /> spending up to a month each year at their [[Powdermill Nature Reserve]].<ref name="RBBP-pan" />
He served on the council of [[English Nature]] from 1996-2002 (and in September 2000 became interim acting chairman for six months).<ref name="EN-acting" /><ref name="RBBP-pan" /> He has been chairman of the [[Cheshire Wildlife Trust]]<ref name="RBBP-pan" /> and a member of the Editorial Board for Ornithology's journal ''Ringing & Migration''.<ref name="EN-acting" /> He was the founder chairman of the Mersey Estuary Conservation Group<ref name="EN-acting" /> and Research Committee of the Liverpool Bay Wader Study Group.<ref name="EN-acting" />
In 2002 he was awarded the [[British Trust for Ornithology]]'s [[Bernard Tucker Medal]] "for his outstanding scientific contributions in surveying, nest-recording and ringing birds".<ref name="BTO-med">{{cite web|url=http://www.bto.org/aboutBTO/accounts/medallists.htm|title=Medallists|date=2006-06-02|publisher=BTO|accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref>
