{{UK-ornithologist-stub}} {{UK-physicist-stub}}

Some individuals and organizations have promoted designs for a [[flag]] representing the planet [[Earth]], though none have been officially recognized as such by any governmental body. The most widely recognized flags associated with Earth are the [[flag of the United Nations]] and the [[Earth Day]] flag.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Listed below are some of the unofficial contenders for a Flag of Earth:
==John McConnell's "Earth Day" flag== [[File:Earth Day Flag.png|thumb|350px|The Earth Day flag, John McConnell's latest proposal]] [[File:EarthFlag1.svg|thumb|350px|McConnell's original design]]
A flag designed by [[John McConnell (peace activist)|John McConnell]] in 1969 for the first [[Earth Day]] is a dark blue field [[Charge (heraldry)|charged]] with ''[[The Blue Marble]]'', a famous [[NASA]] photo of the [[Earth]] as seen from [[outer space]]. The first edition of McConnell's flag used [[screen-printing]] and used different colors: ocean and land were blue and the clouds were white. McConnell presented his flag to the United Nations as a symbol for consideration.<ref name="Weir">{{cite book|last=Weir|title=Peace, Justice, Care of Earth|year=2007|publisher=Press On Publishing|isbn=0971749124}}</ref>
Because of the political views of its creator and its having become a symbol of Earth Day, the flag is associated with [[Environmentalism|environmental awareness]], and the celebration of the global community.<ref name="Weir"/> It was offered for sale originally in the ''[[Whole Earth Catalog]]'', and is the only flag which was endorsed by McConnell. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earthflag.net |title=Authentic Earth Flag |publisher=Earthflag.net |date= |accessdate=2010-10-25}}</ref>
''The Blue Marble'' image was placed in the public domain, and the public nature of this image was the basis of a legal battle that resulted in the invalidation of a trademark and copyright that was originally issued to the Earth Day flag through its original promotional entity, World Equity, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tabberone.com/Trademarks/CopyrightLaw/Copyrightability/articles/EarthFlagVsAlamoFlag_A.shtml|title=Copyright Law - Copyrightability - Articles - Copyright Protection Not Available for Earth Flag|publisher=}}</ref> This does not invalidate the official history of McConnell's flag, only the official documentation that was issued on it.<ref name="Weir"/>
===One Flag in Space=== The One Flag in Space initiative is an offshoot of the Space Generation Congress (SGC), the Space Generation Advisory Council's yearly world meeting. It promotes usage of the ''Blue Marble'' flag for [[space exploration]] (it does not explicitly mention it being McConnell's design).
{{clear}}
==United Nations flag== [[File:Flag of the United Nations.svg|thumb|350px|The [[Flag of the United Nations]]]]
Adopted in 1946, the [[flag of the United Nations]] has been used to indicate world unity, although it technically only represents the [[United Nations]] itself. It has a geographical representation of the planet, and its high visibility usage makes it a well-known contender for representing Earth. During the planning for NASA's moon landings of the 1960s, it was suggested that a UN flag be used in place of the flag of the US.<ref>{{cite web |last=Platoff |first=Anne |title=Where No Flag Has Gone Before: Political and Technical Aspects of Placing a Flag on the Moon (NASA Contractor Report 188251) |publisher=[[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] |date=August 2003 |url=https://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/flag/flag.htm |accessdate=2017-07-14}}</ref>
{{Clear}}
=="World Peace Flag" of Universal Peace Congress== {{main|Peace flag#Earth flag}} [[File:Peace Congress flag.svg|thumb|350px|Van Kirk's World Peace Flag]]
James William van Kirk, a minister from Youngstown, Ohio, designed in 1913 a [[peace flag]] with [[Rainbow flag|rainbow stripes]], stars and a globe. With this flag, he twice made a peace tour through Europe.<ref>Corien Glaudemans, 'Een vredesapostel uit Ohio', in: ''Den Haag Centraal'', 16 oktober 2009.</ref> The [[Universal Peace Congress]] adopted this flag as its World Peace Flag.<ref>Devere Allen, "The Fight for Peace". 1940. p.553.</ref> {{Clear}}
== Olympic flag == [[File:Olympic flag.svg|thumb|right|350px|[[Olympic flag]]]] Designed by [[Pierre de Coubertin]] in 1914 and adopted in [[Olympic games]] since 1920, the [[Olympic flag]] represents all mankind and has a white bar with 5 interlocking rings of 5 colors. The five rings represent the five [[continent]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_1303.pdf|title=The Olympic symbols|publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]]|accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref> The six colors (including the white color of the background) represent all of the world's nations.<ref>http://www.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_1303.pdf</ref> {{Clear}}
== "World Citizen" flag of World Service Authority == [[File:World Citizen Flag.svg|thumb|right|350px|World Citizen flag by Garry Davis]] The [[Global citizenship#World citizen|World Citizen]] is a [[social movement]] for global [[citizenship]] under a proposed [[world government]]. In 1953, one of its activists, [[Garry Davis]], founded the [[World Service Authority]], which sells the [[World Passport]] (a fantasy travel document) with a proposed flag of the world.<ref name="European Council">[http://register.consilium.europa.eu/pdf/en/08/st16/st16225.en08.pdf Table of travel documents entitling the holder to cross the external borders and which may be endorsed with a visa - (Parts II and II) and Part V (documents to which visas cannot be affixed]. [[Council of the European Union]]. 1 December 2008. The World Passport is placed in the latter category.</ref> {{Clear}}
==Astrological Symbol of Earth== [[File:Earth Flag Alt-1.svg|thumb|right|350px|A blue flag with the [[Astrological symbols#Astrological planets|astrological]] [[Earth symbol]] at its center.]] The [[Astrological symbols#Astrological planets|astrological]] (and [[Astronomical symbols|astronomical]]) symbol of Earth is another candidate for Earth's flag, often depicted with a blue background, with the symbol at its center. {{Clear}}
== Other private proposals ==
{{Clear}}
===James W. Cadle's "Flag of Earth"=== [[File:Flag of Earth.svg|thumb|350px|Flag of Earth by James Cadle]] Another Earth flag was created around the same time in 1970 by a farmer from [[Homer, Illinois]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flagofearth.org/flown.html|title=The Flag of Earth - Flown|publisher=}}</ref> named James W. Cadle. Cadle's version of the Earth flag consists of a blue circle representing Earth in the center of the flag, a segment of a large yellow circle representing the sun and a small white circle for the moon, all on a black background. It is particularly popular amongst [[SETI]] researchers and is used by SETI worldwide. {{cn|date=June 2018}} The flag flies at the [[Ohio State University Radio Observatory]] and was lowered to [[half mast]] when [[Carl Sagan]] died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xs4all.nl/~carlkop/sagan.html |title=Carl Sagan |publisher=Xs4all.nl |date= |accessdate=2010-10-25}}</ref> Flag of Earth Co. International was also founded by Cadle which sold the flag. The Flag of Earth became [[public domain]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flagofearth.org/original.html|title=James Cadle's Flag of Earth Home Page|last=Cadle|first=James W.|date=|website=|publisher=North American AstroPhysical Observatory (NAAPO)|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-02|quote="The Flag of Earth is now 34-years-old, and on November 1, 2003, became part of the public domain."}}</ref>
{{Clear}}
===Paul Carroll's "World Flag"=== [[File:The world flag 2006.svg|thumb|right|350px|The combined World Flag in 2006]] The World Flag is an international flag created in 1988 by Paul Carroll to act as a symbol to inspire "positive global change while continuing to embrace and celebrate cultural diversity.<ref name="WorldFlagProjectVision">{{cite web|title=Vision|url=http://www.theworldflag.org/vision.php|website=WorldFlagProject.org|publisher=The World Flag Project|accessdate=30 November 2015|ref=World Flag Project Vision}}</ref>" The current 2008 version of the combined World Flag has a world map 216 flags; including the flags of every [[Member states of the United Nations|UN member state]], the [[United Nations]], and several territories of larger nations.<ref name=WorldFlagProjectVision />
The World Flag has been flown at the [[Headquarters of the United Nations|UN Headquarters]] for the ''A Prayer for Peace'' event, [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|The World Trade Center]], [[Earth Day]] in [[Central Park]], and at various other events around the world.<ref name=WorldFlagProjectHistory>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.theworldflag.org/history.php|website=TheWorldFlag.org|publisher=The World Flag Project|accessdate=30 November 2015|ref=WorldFlagProjectHistory}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Custom Flags|url=http://www.australianflagmakers.com.au/custom-made-flags/|publisher=www.australianflagmakers.com.au}}</ref>
{{Clear}}
===Oskar Pernefeldt's "International Flag of the Planet Earth"=== [[File:International Flag of Planet Earth.svg|thumb|350px|Oskar Pernefeldt’s proposal]] In 2015 a Swedish artist, Oskar Pernefeldt,<ref>{{cite web|title=The International Flag of the Planet Earth|url=http://www.flagofplanetearth.com/#intro-shift|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref> proposed the "International Flag of the Planet Earth".<ref>{{cite web|title = Here’s what the flag of Planet Earth could look like | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2015/05/21/heres-what-the-flag-of-planet-earth-could-look-like/ | accessdate=23 May 2015 | publisher=[[Washington Post]]}}</ref> It was conceived to be used in space expeditions and it has two main purposes: # To be used while representing planet Earth. # To remind the people of Earth that we share this planet, no matter of national boundaries. That we should take care of each other and the planet we live on.
The creators predict that it will be eventually used in Mars landing in 2025 or in a future colony on that planet. The flag is used by space research groups with intent to implanting a base on [[Mars]].<ref>[http://g1.globo.com/fantastico/noticia/2017/11/pesquisador-brasileiro-visita-estacao-no-deserto-que-simula-planeta-marte.html Pesquisador brasileiro visita estação no deserto que simula planeta Marte], [[Fantástico]], November 12, 2017, 4 minutes and 26 seconds of video</ref> The design of the flag consists of seven rings intersecting each other and a deep-blue-sea in the background. The rings are centered on the flag forming a flower in the middle, representing life on Earth. The intersection of the rings represent that all things on Earth are linked directly or indirectly. The rings are organized in a [[Borromean rings]]–like fashion, representing not only the [[seven continents]], but how no part of Earth can be removed without the whole structure collapsing. Finally, the deep-blue represents the ocean and the importance of water for life on Earth.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Nusigma {{!}} This Could Become the Official Flag of Planet Earth|url = http://nusigma.in/official-flag-of-planet-earth/|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160210114338/http://nusigma.in/official-flag-of-planet-earth/|dead-url = yes|archive-date = 2016-02-10|website = nusigma.in|access-date = 2016-02-08}}</ref>
{{Clear}}
===Thomas Mandl's "One World Flag"=== [[File:OWF_One_World_Flag_by_Thomas_Mandl.svg|thumb|right|350px|One World Flag]] The One World Flag is a concept published in 2018 by the German activist and visual artist Thomas Mandl. The design of the flag consists of a blue circle on a translucent blank background. Through the usage of [[Sheer fabrics]], the environment blends into the flag background and thus becomes an integral part of the flag design representing the ever-changing nature of culture, society, politics, and environment of the planet earth. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.br.de/puls/themen/welt/one-world-flag-thomas-mandl-interview-100.html|title=One World, one flag|publisher=Bavarian Broadcasting, BR|accessdate=2018-11-09}}</ref>
{{Clear}}
