{{short description|An international research programme on the fluxes of carbon between the atmosphere and ocean, and within the ocean interior}} {{refimprove|date=August 2018}}
The '''Joint Global Ocean Flux Study''' ('''JGOFS''') was an international [[scientific research|research]] programme on the fluxes of [[carbon]] between the [[atmosphere]] and [[ocean]], and within the ocean interior. Initiated by the [[Scientific Committee of Oceanic Research]] (SCOR), the programme ran from 1987 through to 2003, and became one of the early core projects of the [[International Geosphere-Biosphere Programme]] (IGBP).
The overarching goal of JGOFS was to advance the understanding of, as well as improve the measurement of, the [[biogeochemistry|biogeochemical]] processes underlying the exchange of carbon across the air—sea interface and within the ocean. The programme aimed to study these processes from regional to global spatial scales, and from seasonal to interannual temporal scales, and to establish their sensitivity to external drivers such as [[climate change]].<ref name="about">{{cite web |url=http://ijgofs.whoi.edu/about.html |title=About JGOFS |last= |first= |date= |website=JGOFS |publisher=[[Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution]] |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>
Early in the programme in 1988, two long-term [[time-series]] projects were established in the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] and [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] basins. These — [[Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study]] (BATS)<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0967-0645(00)00148-X | last1 = Steinberg | first1 = D.K. | last2 = Carlson | first2 = C.A. | last3 = Bates | first3 = N.R. | last4 = Johnson | first4 = R.J. | last5 = Michaels | first5 = A.F. | last6 = Knap | first6 = A.H. | year = 2001 | title = Overview of the US JGOFS Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study (BATS): a decade-scale look at ocean biology and biogeochemistry | url = http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/els/09670645/1996/00000043/00000002/art00004;jsessionid=n1jo8swk5e3a.alice | journal = Deep-Sea Research Part II | volume = 48 | issue = 8–9| pages = 1405–1447 }}</ref> and [[Hawaii Ocean Time-series]] (HOT)<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1016/0967-0645(96)00005-7 | last1=Karl |first=D.M. |last2=Lukas |first2=R. |year=1996 |title=The Hawaii Ocean Time-series (HOT) program: Background, rationale and field implementation |journal=Deep-Sea Research Part II |volume=43 |pages=129–156 }}</ref> — continue to make observations of ocean [[hydrography]], [[Ocean chemistry|chemistry]] and [[marine biology|biology]] to the present-day. In 1989, JGOFS undertook the multinational [[North Atlantic Bloom Experiment]] (NABE) to investigate and characterise the annual [[spring bloom]] of [[phytoplankton]], a key feature in the [[carbon cycle]] of the open ocean.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1016/0967-0645(93)90018-I |last1=Harrison |first1=W.G. |last2=Head |first2=E.J.H. |last3=Horne |first3=E.P.W. |last4=Irwin |first4=B. |last5=Li |first5=W.K.W. |last6=Longhurst |first6=A.R. |last7=Paranjape |first7=M.A. |last8=Platt |first8=T. |year=1993 |title=The Western North-Atlantic Bloom Experiment |journal=Deep-Sea Research Part II |volume=40 |pages=279-305 }}</ref>
An important aspect of JGOFS lay in its objective to develop an increased network of observations, made using routine procedures, and curated such that they were easily available to researchers.<ref name="about"/> JGOFS also oversaw the development of models of the marine system based on understanding gained from its observational programme.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0967-0637(99)00010-2 |last1=Evans |first1=G.T. |title=The role of local models and data sets in the Joint Global Ocean Flux Study |year=1999 |journal=Deep-Sea Research Part I |volume=46 |pages=1369-1389 }}</ref>
==See also== * [[Biological pump]] * [[Geochemical Ocean Sections Study]] (GEOSECS) * [[Global Ocean Data Analysis Project]] (GLODAP) * [[Global Ocean Ecosystem Dynamics]] (GLOBEC) * [[Solubility pump]] * [[World Ocean Atlas]] (WOA) * [[World Ocean Circulation Experiment]] (WOCE)
